[{"id":"try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-2#0","metadata":{"content":"Call `sum_numbers` (pure sync tool, runs in the sandbox):","okf_concept":"try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-2","okf_type":"docs","title":"Try the deployed gateway (curl)"}},{"id":"the-executable-skill-line-in-llms-txt-1#0","metadata":{"content":"Under a `## Skills` section, an executable skill is a normal markdown list item followed by an HTML comment carrying a JSON object with `version`, `tool` (path to the `tool.js`), and `tool_sha256` (hex SHA-256 of the `tool.js` bytes):","okf_concept":"the-executable-skill-line-in-llms-txt-1","okf_type":"docs","title":"The executable-skill line in `llms.txt`"}},{"id":"the-executable-skill-line-in-llms-txt-0#0","metadata":{"content":"> **Status: Draft v0.3, adopted.** This format is specified by the > [Executable Skills extension](https://github.com/MauricioPerera/llms-txt-skills/blob/master/docs/ext-executable-skills.md) > of the [llms-txt-skills](https://github.com/MauricioPerera/llms-txt-skills) > standard. This repo is its reference implementation; the spec and this code > are kept aligned (every MUST in the spec is field-","okf_concept":"the-executable-skill-line-in-llms-txt-0","okf_type":"docs","title":"The executable-skill line in `llms.txt`"}},{"id":"security-model-honest-0#0","metadata":{"content":"- **Tool-host isolation.** Tool code runs in a QuickJS-wasm context separate from the Worker's JS. It sees only `registerTool`, `host`, and what the host prelude defines. No `fetch`, no `process`, no globals leak by default. - **Secrets stay outside the sandbox.** In the sync PoC, the platform secret is read from `env.STRIPE_SECRET` on the host side and is never exposed to tool code — the tool can","okf_concept":"security-model-honest-0","okf_type":"docs","title":"Security model (honest)"}},{"id":"why-1#0","metadata":{"content":"mcpwasm removes the trust requirement for the *code*:","okf_concept":"why-1","okf_type":"docs","title":"Why"}},{"id":"why-2#0","metadata":{"content":"- The tool runs in a separate QuickJS-wasm context with no host globals beyond what the host predefines (`registerTool`, `host`). No `fetch`, no `process`, no disk, no secrets. - The platform secret (e.g. a Stripe key) stays on the host side. The tool can only ask the host to perform a *named* internal action via `host.callInternal` (sync host) or a scoped `host.fetchOrigin` (async host). The host","okf_concept":"why-2","okf_type":"docs","title":"Why"}},{"id":"architecture-1#0","metadata":{"content":"- `host.mjs` — synchronous `ToolHost` (sync tools, `host.callInternal` capability). - `host-async.mjs` — `AsyncToolHost` (async handlers, `host.fetchOrigin` capability, resource hardening). - `mcp-core.mjs` / `mcp-core-async.mjs` — JSON-RPC 2.0 MCP core (transport-agnostic). - `worker.mjs` — PoC MCP server (sync host, inline tools). - `worker-spike.mjs` — async spike (fetchHome/fetchEvil). - `work","okf_concept":"architecture-1","okf_type":"docs","title":"Architecture"}},{"id":"try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-0#0","metadata":{"content":"The gateway is live at `https://llmstxt-gateway.rckflr.workers.dev`. It is restricted to origins in its allowlist; the demo site `https://llmstxt-demo-site.rckflr.workers.dev` and the bookstore `https://llmstxt-bookstore.rckflr.workers.dev` (D1-backed, includes a write skill `create_order`) are allowed. `origin` is URL-encoded as a query param. The deployed gateway requires `-H \"Authorization: Bea","okf_concept":"try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-0","okf_type":"docs","title":"Try the deployed gateway (curl)"}},{"id":"try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-4#0","metadata":{"content":"- PoC sync host: `https://toolhost-mcp.rckflr.workers.dev` (POST `/mcp`). - Demo publisher: `https://llmstxt-demo-site.rckflr.workers.dev/llms.txt` (the root path returns 404 by design — only specific routes are served).","okf_concept":"try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-4","okf_type":"docs","title":"Try the deployed gateway (curl)"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-static-mcp-0#0","metadata":{"content":"**Static MCP: your tools are files, not servers.** Tools are published as static, hash-verified content and executed sandboxed on demand. What static site hosting did to web servers — \"don't run Apache, publish HTML\" — this does to MCP servers: don't run an MCP server, publish files. The publisher needs zero infrastructure; the MCP server is materialized per request from those files and evaporates","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-static-mcp-0","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm — Static MCP"}},{"id":"the-executable-skill-line-in-llms-txt-2#0","metadata":{"content":"- The `<!-- skill: {...} -->` comment marks the line as an *executable* skill. List items without it are treated as descriptive-only and ignored by the gateway. - `tool` is resolved relative to the origin. - `tool_sha256` is verified against the fetched `tool.js` bytes before the tool is loaded. Mismatch → the skill is rejected (logged) and not registered. - If the JSON is invalid the line is sile","okf_concept":"the-executable-skill-line-in-llms-txt-2","okf_type":"docs","title":"The executable-skill line in `llms.txt`"}},{"id":"why-0#0","metadata":{"content":"MCP clients (Claude, Cursor, others) can call arbitrary tools. Running a third-party tool's code directly in your backend means that code can read your secrets, hit your DB, phone home, or loop forever. You either trust the author fully or you don't run the tool.","okf_concept":"why-0","okf_type":"docs","title":"Why"}},{"id":"quick-start-1#0","metadata":{"content":"`npm run gateway` is documented as-is from `package.json`; it builds the gateway worker and runs `mf-gateway.mjs` against the real deployed demo site.","okf_concept":"quick-start-1","okf_type":"docs","title":"Quick start"}},{"id":"try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-3#0","metadata":{"content":"Call `server_time` (async tool that calls `host.fetchOrigin(\"/api/time\")` on the allowed origin):","okf_concept":"try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-3","okf_type":"docs","title":"Try the deployed gateway (curl)"}},{"id":"quick-start-0#0","metadata":{"content":"Requirements: Node 18+ and `npm install` (already done in this checkout).","okf_concept":"quick-start-0","okf_type":"docs","title":"Quick start"}},{"id":"architecture-0#0","metadata":{"content":"1. A publisher site ships `/llms.txt` plus per-skill `tool.js` and `SKILL.md` files. `llms.txt` lists each executable skill with a SHA-256 of its `tool.js`. 2. On each request the gateway downloads `llms.txt`, parses the executable skills, downloads each `tool.js`, verifies SHA-256, and loads the verified ones into a fresh `AsyncToolHost` scoped to that origin. 3. Tool code runs inside QuickJS-was","okf_concept":"architecture-0","okf_type":"docs","title":"Architecture"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-static-mcp-2#0","metadata":{"content":"Think \"php-wasm, but for MCP tools\": the platform owner embeds the host, loads `tool.js` files, and each tool runs isolated in a QuickJS WebAssembly sandbox. The only bridge from the sandbox to the platform's internals is an explicit capability the host injects. No capability, no access.","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-static-mcp-2","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm — Static MCP"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-static-mcp-1#0","metadata":{"content":"mcpwasm is the reference implementation: a sandboxed runtime for third-party MCP tools (untrusted tool code inside QuickJS-wasm on Cloudflare Workers), plus a gateway that turns any static site publishing `llms.txt` with executable skills into an MCP server.","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-static-mcp-1","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm — Static MCP"}},{"id":"mcpwasm-static-mcp-3#0","metadata":{"content":"This repo integrates with the [llms-txt-skills](https://github.com/MauricioPerera/llms-txt-skills) standard via a provisional extension for executable skills (see below).","okf_concept":"mcpwasm-static-mcp-3","okf_type":"docs","title":"mcpwasm — Static MCP"}},{"id":"try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-1#0","metadata":{"content":"List the skills the demo site publishes:","okf_concept":"try-the-deployed-gateway-curl-1","okf_type":"docs","title":"Try the deployed gateway (curl)"}}]